  "prompt": "What is the exact truth behind Nikola Tesla and Thomas Edison rivalry?",
  "response": "The rivalry between Nikola Tesla and Thomas Edison is often referred to as the \"War of the Currents.\" This conflict primarily revolved around two competing forms of electrical power transmission: direct current (DC) promoted by Edison, and alternating current (AC) championed by Tesla.\n\nThomas Edison was a staunch advocate of DC power. He had already established a network of DC power stations across the United States and had substantial investments in DC technology. However, DC had limitations, notably in its inability to be transmitted efficiently over long distances due to significant power losses.\n\nNikola Tesla, on the other hand, was a proponent of AC power. Tesla's designs for AC motors and transformers allowed AC to be transmitted over much greater distances with less loss of power. George Westinghouse, an entrepreneur and engineer, saw the potential in Tesla's AC system and began financing and promoting it.\n\nEdison vehemently opposed AC power, partly because it threatened his DC-based business interests. He embarked on a campaign to discredit AC, including public demonstrations where he electrocuted animals to show the supposed dangers of AC power. This included a notorious event where a circus elephant named Topsy was electrocuted. Edison also promoted the idea that AC was too dangerous to be used in households and public places.\n\nDespite Edison's efforts, AC ultimately proved to be more efficient and versatile for power transmission. The \"War of the Currents\" reached a peak with the decision to use AC for powering the electrical grid at the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago, which was a significant victory for Tesla and Westinghouse. Additionally, the successful installation of the first long-distance power transmission line from Niagara Falls using AC technology further solidified its dominance.\n\nIn summary, the rivalry was primarily business-oriented and technically driven. Edison fought to protect his investments in DC, while Tesla and Westinghouse, whose interests lay in the more efficient AC, ultimately won the battle, leading to widespread adoption of AC power systems. Despite their rivalry, both men made significant contributions to the field of electrical engineering and the development of modern electricity infrastructure.",
